# Scene Building - Navigation Hub

## Purpose
Central navigation and overview for scene building frameworks and methodologies. This hub connects to atomic documents containing specific scene-building approaches.

## Classification
- **Domain:** Plot Development - Scene Level
- **Stability:** Stable
- **Abstraction:** Navigation
- **Confidence:** High

## Scene Building Framework Categories

### Foundational Frameworks
- [[dramatic-arc]] - Universal tension patterns for scenes
- [[story-circle]] - Cyclical transformation framework
- [[conflict-types]] - Types and layers of narrative conflict
- [[narrative-causality]] - Cause-and-effect relationships
- [[value-shifts]] - Meaningful changes in value states

### Scene Construction
- [[scene-sequel-structure]] - Action-reaction narrative rhythm
- [[scene-purpose]] - Multi-function scene optimization
- [[scene-tension]] - Creating and maintaining engagement
- [[scene-entrances-exits]] - Beginning and ending scenes effectively
- [[information-management]] - Strategic information distribution

### Analysis and Evaluation
- [[scene-purpose-verification]] - Evaluating narrative effectiveness
- [[tension-evaluation]] - Assessing and improving tension
- [[character-agency]] - Ensuring character-driven scenes
- [[setting-integration]] - Leveraging setting elements
- [[dialogue-effectiveness]] - Improving character exchanges

### Implementation Tools
- [[scene-planning-worksheet]] - Practical planning template
- [[revision-checklist]] - Scene improvement guide
- [[common-problems]] - Troubleshooting scene issues

## Quick Reference

### When to Use These Frameworks
- Planning new scenes from scratch
- Revising existing scenes for impact
- Diagnosing scene problems
- Ensuring scene-level narrative coherence
- Optimizing pacing and engagement

### Key Principles
1. Every scene must create meaningful change
2. Character decisions drive outcomes
3. Multiple purposes optimize narrative economy
4. Tension maintains reader engagement
5. Setting and dialogue serve narrative goals

